<font color="#FF0000">MORE FOR DOC SPATZ,</font><br>
<tt>Thu Aug  7  6:25:00 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Doc Spatz,<br><br>
A few more comments for you.<br><br>
First, I would like to make it clear that most Vietnam Vets had REAL experiences in Vietnam. Consequently, their views and feelings are formed from a trial by fire. A result of this is a characteristic of understatement of our state of affairs. Other than some discomfort in your life, I really don't see anything to compare. Therefore, this display of indignation, character assasination, name calling, and the like, is really reminiscent of the plumage display, noises, and puffed up fret-like dance used by prairie chickens to attract the attention of possible mates. Really, you must admit that since NOTHING happened of significance to disrupt the free expression of your life, all this display on your part is meaningless. It certainly is meaningless to me. <br><br>
Second, if you study the evolution of your arguments, there is always a little bait and switch action, almost like you are using us in a little mind game to sucker us into believing that there is truth behind your assertions of seeing other points of view. This latest string of action around the threads here is replete with really good attempts at control, posturing, and little else. Therefore, to attribute any veracity to your prior comments on this site  in light of this present activity is a mistake on my part.<br><br>
Third, it continues to be my experience that those who protested the war on firm ground have the courage of their convictions and can advance cogent arguments on their position with calm resolve and a willingness to listen. They can debate in the classic manner and do not need to resort to control freak arm waving tactics to have their feelings known and understood. Therefore, anything you advance in support of your cause in your traditional manner is suspect, and not worthy of any consideration by me at all.<br><br>
We seem to have arrived at the true null set. <br><br>
In mathematical terms, the null set is an infinite set of real numbers whose value is zero. Really zero. You can't get much more zero than that.<br><br>
There are Vietnam War protestors with whom I have interacted on the FORUM section of this site, only a small portion of that dialog being presented here, for whom I have the greatest respect and admiration. I do not agree with their positions, but I respect them as worthy human beings. Their respect is mutual. My perception of the state of your cognition of worthiness falls far short of my experiences with others who express similar thematic views. Therefore, any continued interaction with you on this topic is subjecting myself to that which I have found no where else except on the streets, a thoroughly disagreeable and upsetting and hurtfull experience. I hold myself in higher regard than that which would permit me to backslide into an abyss from which I have worked very hard to claw my way out.       
<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


